1 Preliminaries: The site traffic data

The data are from a website for cooking recipes. The company that owns the website wants to sell subscriptions, and the idea is that if the website receives lots of visits (so traffic is high) because of a posted recipe, the likelihood of a subscription sale increases.

Hence the overall objective of this project is to predict which recipes will lead to high traffic.

The raw data set for this project is recipe_site_traffic_2212.csv.

Variable Explanation
recipe unique identifier of recipe
calories number of calories
carbohydrate amount of carbohydrates in grams
sugar amount of sugar in grams
protein amount of protein in grams
category type of recipe. Recipes are listed in one of ten possible groupings (Lunch/Snacks, Beverages, Potato, Vegetable, Meat, Chicken, Pork, Dessert, Breakfast, One Dish Meal).
servings number of servings for the recipe
high_traffic if the traffic to the site was high when this recipe was shown, this is marked with High.

2 The tasks

1- Data wrangling

Specifically, it will be a question of recoding the high_traffic variable and dealing with the missing values.

a- Recoding of variables and validity of the data.

- Recoding the high_traffic variable

traffic$high_traffic <- ifelse(is.na(traffic$high_traffic), 0, 
  ifelse(traffic$high_traffic == "High", 1, 0))
head(traffic,2)
NA

Our variable high-traffic includes a High category and missing values (Na).

Indeed, the high-traffic variable takes the value 1 for all recipes with high traffic (High) and 0 otherwise (represented in our case by Na when the recipes are not visited at all or are less visited on the site).

- Validity of the data

The high_traffic variable becomes a binary numeric variable, taking the value 1 for high-traffic recipes and 0 for the others. This binary structure is particularly suitable for our analysis objectives, especially for the application of the different predicted models (Linear Probability Model, Logit Model and Random Forest Model). These models require a binary dependent variable, which fully justifies the validity of our data.

b- Missing Value Management

traffic %>%
  summarise(across(everything() , ~ mean(is.na(.x) ) ) ) %>%
  select(where(~ .x > 0))

The calorie, carbohydrate, sugar and protein variables have the same number of missing values, i.e.5.49% of missing values, and those for the same individuals. In this specific case, we can delete observations with missing values in the database.

traffic <- drop_na(traffic)

4.Estimation of the Linear Probability Model (LPM) and the Logit Model

- LPM Model

The outcome of interest is a category (High traffic or not). Since Y is binary (0/1), the linear model E(Y|X=x) therefore is a model for the probability of high traffic. If our model is E(Y|X=x)=Pr{Y=1|X=x}=x, we model this probability as a linear index x. This is the linear probability model (LPM).

model <- high_traffic ~ category + calories + carbohydrate + sugar + protein + servings

lpm_model <- lm(model, data = traffic_train)

- Logit Model

This discrete response model is:

E{Y|X=x}=Pr{Y=1|X=x}=G(x)

where G is the logistic distribution G(z)=exp(z)/(1+exp(x))

logit_model <- glm(model, data = traffic_train, family="binomial")

The aim here is to extract the t_value of the two models.

-LMP model

# variable importance: t-statistic

lpm_varimp <- tibble(variable=rownames(lpm_summary$coefficients[-1,]), # drop Intercept

  mutate(variable=factor(variable, levels=variable[order(abs(score))]))
lpm_varimp

The number of servings has a limited impact on traffic, except in the case of servings as a snack.

6- Prediction and comparison of model performance (LPM, Logit, RF)

a- Predictions

- LPM model

lpm_predictions <- predict(lpm_model, newdata = traffic_test, type = "response")

lpm_pred_class <- ifelse(lpm_predictions > 0.5, 1, 0)

traffic_test <- traffic_test %>%
  mutate(lpm_predictions = predict(lpm_model, newdata = traffic_test))

traffic_test %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = lpm_predictions, y = as.numeric(as.character(high_traffic)))) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line(aes(y = lpm_predictions), col = "red") +
  labs(x = "Predicted Probability (LPM)", y = "Probability of High Traffic",
       title = "High Traffic: Model Predictions") +
  theme_bw()

This graph shows how the probabilities predicted by the Linear Probability Model (LPM) compare to the actual probabilities observed. The x-axis (high traffic) represents the true probability, while the y-axis represents the probability predicted by the model. A diagonal red line is drawn to represent a perfect match (the predictions identical to the real probabilities). The dots broadly follow the diagonal line, indicating that the LPM model predicts true probabilities relatively well. However, there is some dispersion around this line, which suggests that the LPM is not perfect in its predictions.

- Logit model

logit_predictions <- predict(logit_model, newdata = traffic_test, type = "response")

This graph compares the probabilities predicted by the logistic model (Logit) to the actual probabilities. The x-axis represents the actual probabilities of high traffic, while the y-axis represents the probabilities predicted by the logit model. The dots are relatively close to the red diagonal line, indicating that the Logit model has a similar performance to the LPM in capturing true probabilities. The dispersion of the points is however slightly lower than that of the LPM, which could indicate that the Logit is slightly better at modeling the true probabilities.

       col = c("blue", "green", "red"), lty = 1)

This graph illustrates the performance of the three models (LPM, Logit, RF) in terms of their ability to correctly distinguish between positive and negative classes. The ROC curve shows the relationship between the true positive rate (sensitivity) and the false positive rate at different decision thresholds. AUC (Area Under the Curve) is a metric that quantifies this performance, with an AUC closer to 1 indicating better performance.

LPM (AUC = 0.827): The LPM model has a very good discriminating ability, with an AUC of 0.827, which is slightly higher than the other models. Logit (AUC = 0.825): The Logit model is almost equivalent to the LPM with an AUC of 0.825, which shows that it also performs very well. RF (AUC = 0.798): The RF model has a slightly lower performance with an AUC of 0.798, although it remains competitive.

c- Model selection

- Summary of results for the Performance of Modls

Model Accuracy Kappa AUC Sensitivity Specificity
Linear Probability Model (LPM) 76.26% 0.5083 0.827 66.23% 83.82%
Logit Model 76.26% 0.5075 0.825 65.58% 84.31%
Random Forest (RF) 73.46% 0.4477 0.802 61.04% 82.84%

- Choice of model

If the goal is only to optimize performance (AUC), LPM can be considered, but Logit remains a more robust and interpretable choice. RF can be ruled out due to its slightly lower performance.

So, the Logit is therefore our preferred choice for its robustness and interpretability. Using its results, it is possible to identify the levers for improvement for site traffic, while implementing concrete solutions to optimize the user experience and marketing campaigns.

we choose the Logit model for three reasons:

  • Balanced performance:Logit is almost equivalent to LPM in terms of Accuracy and AUC, but offers better specificity (84.31%) and a small difference in sensitivity (65.58%).

  • Interpretability:Logit is easy to interpret, which is crucial for understanding the factors contributing to high traffic.

  • Stability:The logit model is less sensitive to problems related to linear assumptions (as in LPM) and more reliable when probabilities are needed.

b- Interpretation of Prdiction result

  • Logit Model:

Accuracy (Global Precision) : 76.26%

This means that 76.26% of the models predictions are correct, whether for observations with high or low traffic. In addition, the accuracy is identical to that of the Linear Probability Model (LPM), which indicates a similar performance in this aspect. High overall accuracy.

Kappa : 0.5075

The Kappa statistic evaluates the agreement between predictions and observed values by taking into account chance. And so, a value of 0.5075 indicates moderate agreement (according to the Landis and Koch scale: between 0.41 and 0.60 corresponds to moderate agreement). This shows that the model is able to predict better than chance, but there is still room for improvement.

Sensitivity (Recall, Positive true rates) : 65.58%

Sensitivity measures the models ability to correctly detect cases where traffic is high. With a sensitivity of 65.58%, the model identifies 65.58% of high-traffic cases correctly, but about 34% of cases are missed (false negatives). A sensitivity of less than 70% indicates that the model could be improved to better detect positive cases.

Specificity (Negative true rate) : 84.31%

Specificity measures the models ability to correctly identify cases where traffic is low. With a specificity of 84.31%, the model correctly identifies the vast majority of cases where traffic is low. This shows that the model performs better for low-traffic cases than for high-traffic cases.

AUC (Area Under the Curve) : 0.825

The AUC measures the models ability to correctly distinguish between positive cases (high traffic) and negative cases (low traffic). And so, a value of 0.825 indicates a very good discriminating ability (an AUC between 0.8 and 0.9 is considered excellent). This means that the model performs well at differentiating between high- and low-traffic observations, but remains slightly below the LPM (AUC = 0.827).

c- Validation of model

From all of the above, we can therefore conclude that the model is good.

d- Reconmmandation for more higher traffic

Strategic improvements on popular categories, the creation of targeted content, and the engagement of visitors through a better user experience and targeted marketing will allow for higher traffic.

  • Create more content around recipe categories that increase the likelihood of high traffic like Potato, Vegetable and Pork by adding popular variations for these categories and highlighting these categories on the homepage.

  • Use keywords related to these categories to improve the SEO of related recipes. For example, Simple vegetarian recipes or Traditional meat dishes etc.

  • Offer innovative recipes for recipe categories that do not increase the likelihood of high traffic such as Breakfast, Chicken and Chicken Breast. For example: Chicken meal in 20 minutes. Also, collaborate with influencers or chefs to create trendy recipes in these categories.

  • Since intermediate portions (2 or 4 or 6) are less relevant than specific portions (servings as a snack), offer specific recipes for snacks and adjust the quantities for larger groups.

  • Add attractive nutritional information to each recipe such as low carb recipe and ideal for weight loss.

  • Use social media to promote different recipes and offer feedback and ratings for users to interact with the recipes.
